The issue you're experiencing is due to the way `ChannelFactory` handles SSL/TLS certificate validation. Unfortunately, setting `ServicePointManager.ServerCertificateValidationCallback` doesn't work in this case because `ChannelFactory` uses a different mechanism for certificate validation.

To bypass certificate validation when using `ChannelFactory`, you can use the `CertificateValidationMode` property on the `BasicHttpBinding` instance. Here's how you can do it:

```csharp
var binding = new BasicHttpBinding
{
    UseDefaultWebProxy = true,
    ProxyCredentialType = HttpProxyCredentialType.None,
    Security = new BasicHttpSecurity
    {
        Mode = BasicHttpSecurityMode.Transport,
        Transport = new HttpTransportSecurity
        {
            ClientCredentialType = HttpClientCredentialType.None,
            // Set the CertificateValidationMode to None
            ClientCertificateValidationMode = X509CertificateValidationMode.None
        }
    }
};

var cf = new ChannelFactory<IMyContract>(binding);
```

By setting `ClientCertificateValidationMode` to `X509CertificateValidationMode.None`, you're essentially telling WCF to bypass certificate validation.

Please note that this approach disables certificate validation entirely, which may not be suitable for production environments. In a production environment, you should use a trusted certificate or add the self-signed certificate to the trusted store.

Alternatively, you can also use a custom certificate validator by implementing the `X509CertificateValidator` class and setting it on the `ClientCertificateValidationMode` property:

```csharp
public class CustomCertificateValidator : X509CertificateValidator
{
    public override void Validate(X509Certificate2 certificate)
    {
        // Custom validation logic here
    }
}

// ...

var binding = new BasicHttpBinding
{
    // ...
    Security = new BasicHttpSecurity
    {
        // ...
        Transport = new HttpTransportSecurity
        {
            // ...
            ClientCertificateValidationMode = X509CertificateValidationMode.Custom,
            CustomCertificateValidator = new CustomCertificateValidator()
        }
    }
};
```

This approach allows you to implement custom validation logic while still maintaining some level of security.

