The issue here is that the function signatures you provided are indeed identical when it comes to the type of the parameter `x`. The `&&` symbol in the first function signature is not doing what you expect it to do. It's not specifying that the function takes an rvalue reference, but rather it's part of the syntax for a forwarding reference, also known as a universal reference.

In C++11 and later, when `&&` is used in a function template parameter, it's a forwarding reference, not an rvalue reference. It's a special type of reference that can bind to both lvalues and rvalues. However, in your case, since the parameter `x` is not a template parameter, `&&` is not a forwarding reference, but rather an rvalue reference.

The problem is that the `const` keyword makes the parameter `x` a const lvalue reference, which can bind to both lvalues and rvalues. This means that the first two function signatures are identical, which is why you're getting a compiler error due to function signature duplication.

To achieve the desired behavior, you can use a technique called "universal references" or "forwarding references" with `std::forward` to forward the argument to the correct function. Here's an example:

```cpp
void fooImpl(double const &x) { /* lvalue handling */ }
void fooImpl(double &&x) { /* rvalue handling */ }

template <typename T>
void foo(T &&x) {
    fooImpl(std::forward<T>(x));
}
```

In this example, `foo` is a function template that takes a forwarding reference `x`. The `std::forward` function is used to forward the argument `x` to `fooImpl`, which will then call the correct overload based on whether `x` is an lvalue or an rvalue.

This technique is less elegant than having separate function signatures, but it's a common pattern in C++11 and later to achieve the desired behavior.

Here's a more complete example with the `foo` function returning `double`:

```cpp
double fooImpl(double const &x) { /* lvalue handling */ return x; }
double fooImpl(double &&x) { /* rvalue handling */ return x; }

template <typename T>
double foo(T &&x) {
    return fooImpl(std::forward<T>(x));
}
```

This way, you can handle both lvalues and rvalues correctly, and the correct `fooImpl` function will be called based on the type of the argument passed to `foo`.

