import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";

const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `Count is ${count}`;
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;

The problem is that every time we click the button, the count updates but the browser title also updates and this can be annoying. So, we want to update the title only when the count reaches a certain number.

Let's say we want to update the title only when the count reaches 5 or more. How can we do that?

output:
To update the title only when the count reaches 5 or more, you can add a conditional statement inside the `useEffect` hook. Here's the modified code:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";

const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    if (count >= 5) {
      document.title = `Count is ${count}`;
    }
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this code, the `useEffect` hook will only update the document title when the `count` is 5 or more. If the `count` is less than 5, the title will not be updated.

However, this might cause the title to be stuck at the initial value if the count never reaches 5. To avoid this, you can also add an initial update to the title when the component mounts:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";

const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `Count is ${count}`;
    const updateTitle = () => {
      if (count >= 5) {
        document.title = `Count is ${count}`;
      }
    };
    updateTitle();
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

But a cleaner way to achieve this is to use a separate state variable to track whether the title should be updated:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";

const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [updateTitle, setUpdateTitle] = useState(false);

  const handleClick = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    if (updateTitle) {
      document.title = `Count is ${count}`;
    }
  }, [count, updateTitle]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (count >= 5) {
      setUpdateTitle(true);
    }
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this code, `updateTitle` is a separate state variable that tracks whether the title should be updated. The first `useEffect` hook updates the title only when `updateTitle` is `true`, and the second `useEffect` hook sets `updateTitle` to `true` when the count reaches 5 or more.

